  "articleSummary": "This analytical article argues that the traditional security model—treating production as dangerous and local development as safe—is obsolete. The author contends that the modern developer laptop has become a \"credential warehouse\" vulnerable to \"boring\" but effective attacks like prompt injection, poisoned dependencies, and misconfigured CI/CD workflows. The intended audience is software engineers and DevOps professionals who must shift from a passive \"compromised\" mindset to an active defense against actions they themselves might inadvertently trigger. Written in a sobering, cautionary tone, the text uses the metaphor of \"half-trusted doors\" and \"agentic automation\" to highlight how increased developer velocity and AI integration have expanded the attack surface.",
